‘We shall not cease from exploration
And the end of all our exploring
Will be to arrive where we started
And know the place for the first time.
Through the unknown, remembered gate
When the last of earth left to discover
Is that which was the beginning;
At the source of the longest river
The voice of the hidden waterfall
And the children in the apple-tree
Not known, because not looked for
But heard, half-heard, in the stillness
Between two waves of the sea.’

—T.S. Eliot

Need a stocking filler? Well, luckily I have just the thing for some Christmas gift inspiration. Whether you want to learn about my adventures along the Nile, Himalayas or the Americas, or my first big overland journey hitchhiking the Silk Road there’s plenty of armchair adventure to be had. 2022. A busy and fortunate year….
Woke up on the beach in Mexico with a hangover and almost bankrupt thanks to Covid, determined to work hard, regain momentum and live a fulfilling year. Went exploring in some bat caves and found ancient Mayan treasure. Caught Covid and a lung fungal infection (from the bats) at the same time- misdiagnosed as pneumonia & almost died. Spent a week in hospital in Costa Rica. Travel insurance saved me £20k. Made a film about Costa Rica. War broke out in Ukraine. Went to Ukraine (with @johnnymercermp) and made a film about that too for @channel4. Then went to India with my old pals @AshBhardwaj & @bonzka and travelled through Ladakh, Kashmir, Punjab & Pakistan (4 part series for @discovery channel coming soon to the UK). Rode a horse and didn’t break my leg. Had my 40th birthday with 200 mates in a tent in Battersea Park. Made a film about the magical island of Procida in Italy. Ate the biggest lemon I ever did see. After buying 320 acres of desert in Colorado I set up a retreat centre in the Rocky Mountains with good friends. Went to Los Angeles where I lost my airpods. In Greece I paid homage to Homer at Ithaca. Filmed desert lions in Namibia for a new series about wildlife. Wilderness festival. Sold my house. South of France to manifest some inspiration and hug some trees. Filmed Orangutans in Borneo. Published book number 10- Endurance, an Anthology. Greece trip #2 Rode a scooter and did break my leg. Surgery, lots of metal and a month in a wheelchair. Worked out who mattered and who didn’t. The Queen died. Wrote a book about Afghanistan with @veteranstateofmind Hobbled round the UK on a 12 city theatre tour with @alex_bescoby Went to COP27 in Egypt. Visits to Holland, Italy and Sweden. Started filming a new project for 2023. Planted some trees. Stonehenge for solstice, back home for tea and Christmas dinner. Slept for a week. No more hangovers. 

Not showing off, i’m just knackered and was remembering why. That’s just the highlights reel of course. There was love, heartbreak and tragedy too, lessons learnt and many failures. But that’s life #Liveit #makeshithappen #followyourdreams #manifestyourreality
Happy 70th Birthday Dad, you continue to be my lifelong inspiration. And Happy New Year all!

Afghanistan, August 2021. As the clock ticks down to a total Allied withdrawal and the Taliban go door to door to execute 'collaborators', a small force of allied Paratroopers and Marines set about evacuating as many Afghans and their families as possible. 

The evacuation of Kabul in August 2021 will go down in military history as one of the most unexpected events in modern times. In an eerie replay of the disastrous British retreat from Kabul in 1842, coalition troops withdrew from Afghanistan after 20 years of military campaigning. The subsequent collapse of the Afghan government and its army shocked the world, as a resurgent Taliban gathered its forces and swept across the country. Thousands of Afghans who had worked with the allies were left to the meagre mercy of the Taliban. 

As the Taliban went door to door to execute 'collaborators', a small international task force set out on a daring mission to evacuate as many Afghans and their families as possible. Drawing on a wide range of first-hand accounts - the politicians and officers who planned the trans-continental rescue, the young soldiers who were faced with the unenviable task of keeping a crowd of thousands of desperate people at bay, former interpreters and soldiers of the Afghan Special Forces who made it out - Escape from Kabul is the harrowing true story of Operation Pitting and the Kabul airlift. Coming soon….

To support the Save Our Wild Isles campaign, the @nationaltrust has created a very special series - The Wild Life - telling the story of different locations they care for, and the work their rangers, volunteers and communities are doing to help protect these natural habitats from the very real threats of climate change.

For part 1 of the series, I recently visited the Farne Islands @northumberlandcoastnt - home to possibly the most exciting sea bird colony in England - including between 30,000 and 40,000 breeding pairs of puffins, and also one of the most important grey seal pupping sites in England.

‘An important account of one of the defining moments of the modern world’ -- @peterfrankopan

‘An essential contribution to the historical record, told with lucid flair’ -- @sophy_roberts

Through an accumulation of eye witness reports, Levison Wood reveals the true horror and scale of the Afghan suffering and the heroic efforts of the British and American troops and veterans during the August 2021 evacuation from Kabul. Vividly told, Escape from Kabul captures the human cost of America's deal with the Taliban’-- Larisa Brown

‘Escape from Kabul is savage, adrenalin-fuelled, brutally honest, compelling, and essential reading. Wood and Jones are a dream team writing about a nightmare. These are the stories that soldiers tell each other when the press and politicians have packed up and moved on. These are the real stories of the men and women who snatched honour from the jaws of humiliating betrayal and defeat’ -- @ben.timberlake_high.risk 

‘Escape From Kabul explains through personal knowledge and eye-witness testimony the bravery, endurance and professionalism of men and women tasked with achieving the near-impossible’ -- Stuart Ramsay, Chief Correspondent, @skynews

Over the course of six months, @levison.wood trekked more than 1,700 miles across the roof of the world: Along the Silk Route in Afghanistan, the Line of Control between Pakistan and India, the disputed territories of Kashmir, and the earthquake-ravaged steppes of Nepal, walking the entire length of the Himalayas. 
Yet it was in a car, during a Maoist strike in Nepal, that he experienced one of the most horrific incidents on that epic walk.

His story appeared as a Moment article in @sidetrackedmag Volume Seven.

I’ve spent the last couple of weeks high in the Arctic circle filming with the local Inuit community for a very exciting new project which will be announced soon.

It’s been one of the more challenging expeditions I’ve been on due to the brutal cold and weather conditions. Temperatures have regularly been below -18 degrees Celsius and camping out in that ain’t fun! But it’s been worth it to get a glimpse into a traditional way of life that is remarkably intact despite the pressures of modernity and of course climate change. #Greenland #expedition #travel #adventure

Photographs from Sudan
Watching the news right now stirs a lot of emotion. Sudan is one of my favourite countries, with some of the most welcoming and friendly people in the world. Back in 2014 I walked the length of the country as part of my Nile expedition and was greeted everywhere I went with overwhelming hospitality. It’s a beautiful place, steeped in an ancient, mystical and magnificent history. It’s so sad to see the violence going on and my thoughts are with my friends living there. I hope that my colleagues in the military and FCDO are able to undertake their rescue mission swiftly.
All photos taken on my #leicam240

‘I don't like either the word [hike] or the thing. People ought to saunter in the mountains - not 'hike!' Do you know the origin of that word saunter? It's a beautiful word. Away back in the middle ages people used to go on pilgrimages to the Holy Land, and when people in the villages through which they passed asked where they were going they would reply, 'A la sainte terre', 'To the Holy Land.' And so they became known as sainte-terre-ers or saunterers. Now these mountains are our Holy Land, and we ought to saunter through them reverently, not 'hike' through them.’
~John Muir

THE ART OF EXPLORATION

‘’You have shown that you are a curious individual, and curiosity is what drives exploration. It is the essence of humanity. Our ability to ask questions, to learn and to share that knowledge is what has made our species the most successful on the planet. Exploration is hardwired into our DNA, so if you feel like you are sometimes consumed by an urge to discover new things, to travel or to explore, then you are not alone. Because it is who we are.

Too often we can feel like passengers in our own lives. This is because we have surrendered our curiosity to other people. We let them make our decisions, and tell us what shape our lives will take. We let fear and mistrust guide us; we become scared of change. We allow ourselves to fall into a rut – our comfort zones – and fail to appreciate new things. We forget that when you retrieve your own curiosity, you can begin to take back control of your life and start sitting in the driving seat.

Life is all about making choices. Being human is all about making choices; but we can only make those choices when we recognise first that we have them by taking ownership of our lives and taking the relevant action. There is much in the world beyond our control, but that it is no reason to surrender the huge amount of power that we do have over our own lives.

There is one unexplored journey to be had for each and every one of us, and that is in the quest for self-discovery – to live a meaningful life. This kind of exploration traverses more than the physical realm, but the treasures are perhaps even more rewarding.

What is for sure is that we can all be explorers in our own right if only we adopt the right thought process. So forget routine; now is the time to embrace the unknown, step out of your comfort zone and open the gateway to the Art of Exploration.’’

Extract from my book ‘The Art of Exploration’ 2021

It’s World Lion Day. 🦁 Lions are one of the most vulnerable species on the planet, with only 25,000 left in the wild.

Lions play a vital role in maintaining the balance of ecosystems, contributing to the overall health and biodiversity of our planet. Today lions are facing numerous threats, including habitat loss, poaching, and conflicts with humans. It is our responsibility to protect and conserve their habitats, ensuring a future where these magnificent creatures can thrive.

Together, we can make a difference! Support organizations working tirelessly to protect lions and their habitats, spread awareness about their conservation, and take action to preserve their existence. As a proud ambassador for @tusk_org I have seen first hand the importance of community engagement in conservation across Africa.

Cenote exploration in the Yucatan

The sink holes or ‘cenotes’ of the Yucatan Peninsula hold a rich and intriguing history that stretches back thousands of years. These natural sinkholes have played a significant role in the lives of the indigenous Mayan people and continue to captivate visitors with their deep cultural significance.

To the ancient Mayans, cenotes were considered sacred portals to the underworld, known as Xibalba. They believed that these mystical water sources were inhabited by powerful deities, who controlled the flow of life-giving water and played a pivotal role in their religious ceremonies.

Cenotes were also vital for the survival of Mayan communities, serving as their primary source of freshwater in the region's dense jungle environment. These natural wells provided a reliable supply of water in an otherwise challenging landscape, sustaining both human and animal populations.

The Mayans recognized the spiritual and practical importance of cenotes, and as a result, many of their cities and settlements were built around these natural formations. Magnificent archaeological sites such as Chichen Itza, Tulum, and Coba are all in proximity to cenotes, showcasing their integral role in Mayan civilization.

Archaeological excavations around cenotes have revealed a treasure trove of artifacts, offering glimpses into the daily lives and rituals of the ancient Mayans. These discoveries have provided valuable insights into their agricultural practices, religious beliefs, and social structures.

Its possible to dive some of these historical wonders and gain a deeper appreciation for the Mayan culture that thrived in this region. Many of the sink holes contain artificers and even the odd human skull- a reminder of the dark history of human sacrifice in the region.

#YucatanCenotes #MayanCulture #ArchaeologicalWonders #CulturalHeritage #AncientCivilizations #ExploringHistory

The power and importance of trees lies in their unparalleled ability to sustain life on earth. From the moment we take our first breath, trees gift us with the very air we need to survive. Through the process of photosynthesis, they absorb carbon dioxide and release oxygen, creating a delicate balance that allows all animal life to flourish. This symbiotic relationship is existential proof of our common heritage. We share 45% of our DNA with trees. Trees are the very reason that we humans are able to exist at all. We owe them everything.

Beyond their role as oxygen providers, forests are also integral components of the global ecosystem. They serve as complex habitats for an astonishing array of flora and fauna, supporting a delicate web of interdependence. Every organism, from the towering trees to the smallest insects, plays a crucial role in maintaining the biodiversity that sustains our planet. The intricate relationships woven within forests are the threads that hold our world together.

And yet, despite their immeasurable value, trees face unprecedented threats. The wanton destruction of these invaluable habitats poses a grave danger to our very survival as a species. The consequences of deforestation reverberate across the globe, from the loss of biodiversity to the release of greenhouse gases and the exacerbation of climate change. As we witness the alarming rate at which forests are cleared to make way for agriculture, logging, and urbanisation, we must confront the devastating impact of our actions- before it’s too late.

We were soldiers once…and young. 15 years ago I served in Afghanistan with the Parachute Regiment on operations to fight the Taliban. I was lucky, I didn’t lose any of my men and I came back in one piece. But there are plenty of tragic stories from those less fortunate. I have no enmity toward the Taliban or those who chose to fight. In war, it is futile to take things personally. The poppy represents the end of war. It represents peace- not nationalism, not the glorification of war, just a simple act of remembrance and thanks to all those who served, and for those who paid the ultimate sacrifice- in all wars- for our current freedom. I look back on my time in Afghanistan with mixed feelings. The sad state of affairs in that country now demonstrates that war is often a vain exercise and should only ever be the last resort. Sadly, even with all the lessons of history behind us, people still too often jump at the opportunity to fight without realising the consequences of that violence. As Churchill said it’s better to Jaw-jaw than war-war. Right now the world stand on the precipice of yet more unnecessary bloodshed. Hopefully common sense and good will prevail over the forces of ego and destruction. #lestweforget #remembranceday #remembrancesunday #utrinqueparatus

In a chaotic world where conflict has become an all too apparent feature on our television screens it’s easy to become immune to the fact that the victims of these conflicts are real people with lives and families. This week I am travelling to the Donbas region of Ukraine which, almost two years after the Russian invasion, is still on the front line of this ongoing war. Millions of people have been forced from their homes, thousands killed and huge parts of the country have been destroyed. Brave Ukrainian soldiers continue to fight daily in the trenches, and now the snows have arrived conditions are truly horrendous. I’m well aware that the world’s attention has now diverted away from Ukraine, and this post is not intended to in any way detract from the dreadful things going on in Gaza right now but don’t forget that it’s here in the Donbas that the future of European security lies. #ukraine #photography #documentary #slavaukraini

Images from the front. 
The Donbas is a place that has seen fighting for generations. It witnessed brutal conflict in World War Two when the Nazis invaded, and since 2014 Ukrainians have been fighting the Russians. Currently there’s a feeling of despondency because of the ongoing stalemate. But beyond the headlines this is a magical land filled with ancient forests and a sublime beauty. As snows fall for a third time in this current war I wish Ukraine every success and hope that peace will return soon. 
#ukraine #donbas #donbass #forests #nature #photography #naturephotography

The last week I have been meeting some incredibly inspiring people on the frontlines of conservation in Ukraine: Soldiers, scientists, environmentalists, all battling to save Ukraines forests. 
The first winter snows fell bringing temperatures to well below freezing making life very tough for those operating in the field as well as for the locals who survive under the threat of constant bombardment. 
The second photo is of a truly heroic individual I met- Sergei Skoryk- the director of Kamyinska Sich National Park. In February 2022 when the Russians invaded he was a civilian environmentalist, when he was captured for a week and interrogated along with several others from a nearby village. He was then ordered to dig a hole- his own grave. Somehow, he managed to escape when his captors were not looking, and swam across the Dnipro river (on a frosty February morning) to safety. He joined the Ukrainian army and continued to work inside the national park safeguarding nature. 

Big thanks to @tellusconservation for organising 📸@jodybragger @aitkenangus 🎥 @bonzka @charlesmcbryde @kalash_pow @laurelchor

From the blurb:

‘100 of the most astonishing stories of human survival, adventure and exploration, chosen by Levison Wood.’

We are always captivated by tales of courage and bravery, of world-firsts and death-defying experiences. In this anthology, explorer and bestselling author Levison Wood has gathered 100 of the most fascinating accounts of human endurance throughout history. From the heroism of Antarctic explorers to pioneering women in the Middle East; from record-breaking athletes to survivors of war and torture, this wide-ranging collection embraces both classics of the genre, as well as new and neglected voices. The extracts are organised around a range of themes; you will find those who sought out new frontiers, or who purposely tested their physical limits in full knowledge of the dangers or risks they might face, but also those who endured persecution and suffering, or were thrust into life or death situations yet defied the odds to survive.

Endurance is packed full of you-couldn't-make-it-up true stories and adventure fiction classics, from the high seas to the poles, from inhospitable jungles and deserts to the unknown realms of space, through physical and mental despair to euphoric highs. Yet all of these extraordinary stories celebrate the enduring nature of the human spirit, and show the mental and physical determination it sometimes takes to achieve one's aims.

This varied and compelling collection will take you on an adventure around the world, but also on an emotional journey exploring what it means to be human.

Includes extracts about and by Ernest Shackleton, Robert Falcon Scott, Sir Edmund Hillary, Tenzing Norgay, Amelia Earhart, Marie Colvin, John Krakauer, Solomon Northrup, Ella Maillart, Freya Stark, Ed Stafford, Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn, Aron Lee Ralston, María Elena Moyano, Gertrude Bell, Isabelle Eberhart, Nellie Bly, Alex Honnold, Nelson Mandela, David Nott, Jules Verne, Neil Armstrong and Scott Kelly.

One of these trees is Methuselah, at 4800 years, it is claimed by the US Forestry service to be the oldest tree in the world (sorry my American friends it’s not quite true. There’s one in wales which is probably 5000, and one in Sweden that’s 9500, although it’s a clone). Methuselah isn’t marked on any official maps and is deliberately hidden from the public so as not to be vandalised or worse. 

It’s a Bristlecone Pine and while they look a bit bedraggled, they’re very much alive. Having shed their needles and store moisture in their deep root systems they are able to survive droughts, fires and deep cold. 

Amazing to think this tree is older than the pyramids and mammoths were wandering around when it was a sapling.

Memorial to an explorer

I finally got the chance to visit a place I’ve been dreaming of since I was a young boy fascinated by history and exploration. The obelisk stands as a testament to the significant and complex impact that British navigator Captain James Cook had on the islands of Hawaii. Hidden amongst a bushy enclave in Kealakekua Bay, the memorial marks the spot where Cook was killed in 1779. 

Cook’s arrival had a profound influence on the islands. He is often credited with opening the door for European exploration and trade in the region. His voyages certainly brought new technologies, plants, and animals to the islands, forever altering the cultural and ecological landscape. He also played a role in mapping and documenting the Pacific, contributing to our understanding of the world. He was a talented sailor, cartographer and fearless leader. I certainly grew up admiring his achievements. But then I wasn’t quite so read in to the way he went about his travels.

Cook’s reputation in Hawaii is complex. While initially seen as a god-like figure by the locals, tensions arose during his third visit to the islands. Many of the indigenous community grew weary of the British captain’s presence and the impact of European contact on their way of life. Cook was by any standards abusive and exploitative of the native inhabitants he met in various places and took to stealing important cultural items from the locals (and allegedly a chiefs wife) This led to a confrontation in Kealakekua Bay, where he was killed by the offended King.

The circumstances surrounding Cook’s death further complicates his legacy in Hawaii. While some consider him a heroic explorer who made significant contributions to the world’s knowledge, others view him as a symbol of the negative impacts of European imperialism and its consequences for indigenous cultures. 

Either way, his memory lives on and the Union Flag remains as part of the Hawaiian state flag, a reminder that it was once voluntarily under the protection of the British Empire (at the request of the Hawaiian King) but never formally colonised until the Americans pinched it in 1898

Probably the best stars in the world ✨ 🌋 🌒 🪄 🌺 

The view from the summit of Mauna Kea, the tallest Volcano on Hawaii, out towards Mauna Loa, the largest Volcano in the world. Both volcanos are host to world class observatories which operate year round above the clouds. Both volcanoes are also sacred mountains. In Hawaiian traditions of creation, the Earth Mother, Papahānaumoku, and the Sky Father, Wākea, created the Islands, with Hawai‘i Island being the first. Mauna Kea is considered to be ‘kupuna’, the first born, and is held in high esteem as a place of spiritual sanctity.

Hawaiians- descendants of ancient Polynesian navigators-were great explorers, and, like the astronomers of today, were captivated by the night sky. The stars, then as now, were their guides.

“As you set out for Ithaka
hope your road is a long one,
full of adventure, full of discovery.
Laistrygonians, Cyclops,
angry Poseidon—don’t be afraid of them:
you’ll never find things like that on your way
as long as you keep your thoughts raised high,
as long as a rare excitement
stirs your spirit and your body.
Laistrygonians, Cyclops,
wild Poseidon—you won’t encounter them
unless you bring them along inside your soul,
unless your soul sets them up in front of you.

Hope your road is a long one.
May there be many summer mornings when,
with what pleasure, what joy,
you enter harbors you’re seeing for the first time;
may you stop at Phoenician trading stations
to buy fine things,
mother of pearl and coral, amber and ebony,
sensual perfume of every kind—
as many sensual perfumes as you can;
and may you visit many Egyptian cities
to learn and go on learning from their scholars.

Keep Ithaka always in your mind.
Arriving there is what you’re destined for.
But don’t hurry the journey at all.
Better if it lasts for years,
so you’re old by the time you reach the island,
wealthy with all you’ve gained on the way,
not expecting Ithaka to make you rich.

Ithaka gave you the marvelous journey.
Without her you wouldn’t have set out.
She has nothing left to give you now.

And if you find her poor, Ithaka won’t have fooled you.
Wise as you will have become, so full of experience,
you’ll have understood by then what these Ithakas mean.”

~Cavafy
